{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775901603497,"sessionID":"ses_28406c2a0ffebaRCAelXVCmpr2","part":{"id":"prt_d7bfbf446001lDvy1P41YTVba9","messageID":"msg_d7bfbd2c3001lZVX1ijj8rtFpI","sessionID":"ses_28406c2a0ffebaRCAelXVCmpr2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_eb3b533fe9764a7ab649e87a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/data-plane.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/data-plane.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: sidebar_position: 2\n3: title: Data Plane API\n4: description: Router proxy and PicoD internal API reference\n5: keywords: [api, data-plane, router, picod, proxy, code-execution]\n6: ---\n7: \n8: # Data Plane API\n9: \n10: The Data Plane API consists of two layers:\n11: \n12: 1. **Router API** — Session-aware HTTP proxy endpoints for invoking AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter sandboxes\n13: 2. **PicoD API** — Internal API running inside sandbox pods for code execution and file operations\n14: \n15: ---\n16: \n17: ## Router Proxy Endpoints\n18: \n19: The Router acts as a reverse proxy that forwards HTTP requests to the correct sandbox pod based on session state stored in Redis/Valkey.\n20: \n21: **Base URL:** `http://<router-host>:<port>` (default port: `8080`)\n22: \n23: All `/v1/` endpoints require Bearer token authentication via the `Authorization` header.\n24: \n25: ---\n26: \n27: ### AgentRuntime Invocation\n28: \n29: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path\" description=\"Proxy requests to an AgentRuntime sandbox session\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n30: \n31: <ApiEndpoint method=\"POST\" path=\"/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path\" description=\"Proxy requests to an AgentRuntime sandbox session\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n32: \n33: Routes HTTP requests to an AgentRuntime sandbox. On the first request for a given session, the Router automatically creates a new session and provisions a sandbox pod via the WorkloadManager.\n34: \n35: #### Path Parameters\n36: \n37: | Parameter | Type | Required | Description |\n38: |-----------|------|----------|-------------|\n39: | `namespace` | string | Yes | Kubernetes namespace of the AgentRuntime CR |\n40: | `name` | string | Yes | Name of the AgentRuntime CR |\n41: | `*path` | string | No | Wildcard path forwarded to the sandbox pod |\n42: \n43: #### Headers\n44: \n45: | Header | Required | Description |\n46: |--------|----------|-------------|\n47: | `Authorization` | Yes | Bearer token for authentication |\n48: | `x-agentcube-session-id` | No | Existing session ID for session affinity. If omitted, a new session is created |\n49: \n50: #### Session Auto-Creation\n51: \n52: When a request arrives without an existing session (no `x-agentcube-session-id` header or the session has expired):\n53: \n54: 1. Router generates a new session ID\n55: 2. Router sends a provisioning request to the WorkloadManager (`POST /api/v1/sandboxes`)\n56: 3. WorkloadManager creates the sandbox pod\n57: 4. Router caches the session-to-pod mapping in Redis/Valkey\n58: 5. Router forwards the original request to the sandbox\n59: 6. Router returns the response with `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n60: \n61: #### Response Headers\n62: \n63: | Header | Description |\n64: |--------|-------------|\n65: | `x-agentcube-session-id` | The session ID for this request. Use this header for subsequent requests to maintain session affinity |\n66: \n67: #### curl Example\n68: \n69: ```bash\n70: # First request — creates a new session\n71: curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/v1/namespaces/default/agent-runtimes/my-agent/invocations/chat \\\n72:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" \\\n73:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n74:   -d '{\"message\": \"Hello\"}'\n75: \n76: # Subsequent requests — reuse the session ID\n77: curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/v1/namespaces/default/agent-runtimes/my-agent/invocations/chat \\\n78:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" \\\n79:   -H \"x-agentcube-session-id: sess-a1b2c3d4\" \\\n80:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n81:   -d '{\"message\": \"Follow up\"}'\n82: ```\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ### CodeInterpreter Invocation\n87: \n88: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path\" description=\"Proxy requests to a CodeInterpreter sandbox session\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n89: \n90: <ApiEndpoint method=\"POST\" path=\"/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path\" description=\"Proxy requests to a CodeInterpreter sandbox session\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n91: \n92: Routes HTTP requests to a CodeInterpreter sandbox. Similar to AgentRuntime invocation but targets CodeInterpreter CRs, which use the PicoD code execution engine internally.\n93: \n94: #### Path Parameters\n95: \n96: | Parameter | Type | Required | Description |\n97: |-----------|------|----------|-------------|\n98: | `namespace` | string | Yes | Kubernetes namespace of the CodeInterpreter CR |\n99: | `name` | string | Yes | Name of the CodeInterpreter CR |\n100: | `*path` | string | No | Wildcard path forwarded to the sandbox pod |\n101: \n102: #### Difference from AgentRuntime Invocation\n103: \n104: | Aspect | AgentRuntime | CodeInterpreter |\n105: |--------|-------------|-----------------|\n106: | CR Type | `AgentRuntime` | `CodeInterpreter` |\n107: | Internal Engine | Custom application | PicoD code execution engine |\n108: | Auth Mode | Bearer token | Configurable (`picod` or `none`) |\n109: | Use Case | Long-running agent services | On-demand code execution |\n110: \n111: #### curl Example\n112: \n113: ```bash\n114: curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/v1/namespaces/default/code-interpreters/python-sandbox/invocations/api/execute \\\n115:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" \\\n116:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n117:   -d '{\"command\": [\"python\", \"-c\", \"print(2+2)\"]}'\n118: ```\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ### Router Health Checks\n123: \n124: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/health/live\" description=\"Liveness probe — returns alive if the Router process is running\" auth=\"none\" />\n125: \n126: Returns a simple liveness check response. Used by Kubernetes liveness probes.\n127: \n128: #### Response — 200 OK\n129: \n130: ```json\n131: {\n132:   \"status\": \"alive\"\n133: }\n134: ```\n135: \n136: #### curl Example\n137: \n138: ```bash\n139: curl http://localhost:8080/health/live\n140: ```\n141: \n142: ---\n143: \n144: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/health/ready\" description=\"Readiness probe — returns ok if the session manager is available\" auth=\"none\" />\n145: \n146: Returns a readiness check response. Verifies that the session manager (Redis/Valkey connection) is operational.\n147: \n148: #### Response — 200 OK\n149: \n150: ```json\n151: {\n152:   \"status\": \"ok\"\n153: }\n154: ```\n155: \n156: #### curl Example\n157: \n158: ```bash\n159: curl http://localhost:8080/health/ready\n160: ```\n161: \n162: ---\n163: \n164: ## PicoD Internal API\n165: \n166: PicoD is the code execution engine running inside CodeInterpreter sandbox pods. It provides endpoints for executing commands and managing files.\n167: \n168: **Base URL:** `http://<sandbox-pod-ip>:<port>` (typically accessed through the Router proxy)\n169: \n170: All `/api/` endpoints require JWT public-key authentication (when `authMode` is set to `\"picod\"`).\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ### Code Execution\n175: \n176: <ApiEndpoint method=\"POST\" path=\"/api/execute\" description=\"Execute a command inside the sandbox\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n177: \n178: Executes a command within the sandbox environment with configurable timeout, working directory, and environment variables.\n179: \n180: #### Request Body\n181: \n182: | Field | Type | Required | Description |\n183: |-------|------|----------|-------------|\n184: | `command` | array of strings | Yes | Command and arguments (e.g., `[\"python\", \"-c\", \"print('hello')\"]`) |\n185: | `timeout` | string | No | Execution timeout as a duration string (e.g., `\"30s\"`, `\"5m\"`). Default: `60s` |\n186: | `working_dir` | string | No | Working directory for command execution (must be within sandbox workspace) |\n187: | `env` | object | No | Environment variables as key-value pairs |\n188: \n189: #### Request Example\n190: \n191: ```json\n192: {\n193:   \"command\": [\"python\", \"-c\", \"print('Hello, World!')\"],\n194:   \"timeout\": \"30s\",\n195:   \"working_dir\": \"/workspace\",\n196:   \"env\": {\n197:     \"PYTHONPATH\": \"/workspace/lib\"\n198:   }\n199: }\n200: ```\n201: \n202: #### Response — 200 OK\n203: \n204: | Field | Type | Description |\n205: |-------|------|-------------|\n206: | `stdout` | string | Standard output from the command |\n207: | `stderr` | string | Standard error output |\n208: | `exitCode` | integer | Process exit code (124 for timeout) |\n209: | `startTime` | string | ISO 8601 timestamp of execution start |\n210: | `endTime` | string | ISO 8601 timestamp of execution end |\n211: | `duration` | number | Execution duration in seconds |\n212: \n213: #### Response Example\n214: \n215: ```json\n216: {\n217:   \"stdout\": \"Hello, World!\\n\",\n218:   \"stderr\": \"\",\n219:   \"exitCode\": 0,\n220:   \"startTime\": \"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\n221:   \"endTime\": \"2024-01-01T00:00:01Z\",\n222:   \"duration\": 0.5\n223: }\n224: ```\n225: \n226: #### Timeout Behavior\n227: \n228: When a command exceeds the specified timeout:\n229: - `exitCode` is set to `124`\n230: - `stderr` includes a message: `\"command timed out after Xs\"`\n231: \n232: #### Authentication\n233: \n234: PicoD uses JWT public-key authentication:\n235: - The Router injects a JWT token into requests forwarded to PicoD\n236: - PicoD validates the token using a pre-loaded public key\n237: - The public key is provided via the `PICOD_JWT_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable\n238: \n239: #### curl Example\n240: \n241: ```bash\n242: curl -X POST http://localhost:8081/api/execute \\\n243:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <jwt-token>\" \\\n244:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n245:   -d '{\n246:     \"command\": [\"python\", \"-c\", \"print(2+2)\"],\n247:     \"timeout\": \"10s\"\n248:   }'\n249: ```\n250: \n251: ---\n252: \n253: ### File Upload\n254: \n255: <ApiEndpoint method=\"POST\" path=\"/api/files\" description=\"Upload files to the sandbox (supports multipart/form-data and JSON base64)\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n256: \n257: Uploads files to the sandbox workspace. Supports two upload methods:\n258: \n259: **Method 1: Multipart Form Data**\n260: \n261: ```bash\n262: curl -X POST http://localhost:8081/api/files \\\n263:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <jwt-token>\" \\\n264:   -F \"file=@./local_file.py\" \\\n265:   -F \"path=/workspace/\"\n266: ```\n267: \n268: **Method 2: JSON Base64**\n269: \n270: ```json\n271: {\n272:   \"path\": \"/workspace/script.py\",\n273:   \"content\": \"cHJpbnQoJ0hlbGxvJykK\"\n274: }\n275: ```\n276: \n277: | Field | Type | Required | Description |\n278: |-------|------|----------|-------------|\n279: | `path` | string | Yes | Destination path in the sandbox |\n280: | `content` | string | Yes (JSON mode) | Base64-encoded file content |\n281: \n282: ---\n283: \n284: ### File Listing\n285: \n286: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/api/files\" description=\"List files in a directory within the sandbox\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n287: \n288: Lists the contents of a directory in the sandbox workspace.\n289: \n290: #### Query Parameters\n291: \n292: | Parameter | Type | Required | Description |\n293: |-----------|------|----------|-------------|\n294: | `path` | string | No | Directory path to list. Default: workspace root |\n295: \n296: #### Response Example\n297: \n298: ```json\n299: {\n300:   \"path\": \"/workspace\",\n301:   \"entries\": [\n302:     {\n303:       \"name\": \"script.py\",\n304:       \"type\": \"file\",\n305:       \"size\": 1024,\n306:       \"modified\": \"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\"\n307:     },\n308:     {\n309:       \"name\": \"data\",\n310:       \"type\": \"directory\",\n311:       \"modified\": \"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\"\n312:     }\n313:   ]\n314: }\n315: ```\n316: \n317: #### curl Example\n318: \n319: ```bash\n320: curl \"http://localhost:8081/api/files?path=/workspace\" \\\n321:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <jwt-token>\"\n322: ```\n323: \n324: ---\n325: \n326: ### File Download\n327: \n328: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/api/files/*path\" description=\"Download a file from the sandbox (streaming)\" auth=\"bearer\" />\n329: \n330: Downloads a file from the sandbox workspace. The file content is streamed in the response body.\n331: \n332: #### Path Parameters\n333: \n334: | Parameter | Type | Required | Description |\n335: |-----------|------|----------|-------------|\n336: | `*path` | string | Yes | Path to the file within the sandbox workspace |\n337: \n338: #### curl Example\n339: \n340: ```bash\n341: curl http://localhost:8081/api/files/workspace/output.csv \\\n342:   -H \"Authorization: Bearer <jwt-token>\" \\\n343:   -o output.csv\n344: ```\n345: \n346: ---\n347: \n348: ### PicoD Health Check\n349: \n350: <ApiEndpoint method=\"GET\" path=\"/health\" description=\"PicoD health check — returns service name, version, and uptime\" auth=\"none\" />\n351: \n352: Returns the health status of the PicoD service, including version information and uptime.\n353: \n354: #### Response — 200 OK\n355: \n356: ```json\n357: {\n358:   \"status\": \"ok\",\n359:   \"service\": \"PicoD\",\n360:   \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\n361:   \"uptime\": \"2h30m15s\"\n362: }\n363: ```\n364: \n365: #### curl Example\n366: \n367: ```bash\n368: curl http://localhost:8081/health\n369: ```\n\n(End of file - total 369 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nsidebar_position: 2\ntitle: Data Plane API\ndescription: Router proxy and PicoD internal API reference\nkeywords: [api, data-plane, router, picod, proxy, code-execution]\n---\n\n# Data Plane API\n\nThe Data Plane API consists of two layers:\n\n1. **Router API** — Session-aware HTTP proxy endpoints for invoking AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter sandboxes\n2. **PicoD API** — Internal API running inside sandbox pods for code execution and file operations\n\n---\n\n## Router Proxy Endpoints\n\nThe Router acts as a reverse proxy that forwards HTTP requests to the correct sandbox pod based on session state stored in Redis/Valkey.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/data-plane.md","time":{"start":1775901603482,"end":1775901603495}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775901604167,"sessionID":"ses_28406c2a0ffebaRCAelXVCmpr2","part":{"id":"prt_d7bfbf6e8001W7bQwYMy4ZMLEv","messageID":"msg_d7bfbd2c3001lZVX1ijj8rtFpI","sessionID":"ses_28406c2a0ffebaRCAelXVCmpr2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1fda8c8748c04770a2b75d6c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/crds.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/crds.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: sidebar_position: 3\n3: title: CRD Reference\n4: description: Kubernetes Custom Resource Definitions for AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter, and Sandbox\n5: keywords: [crd, kubernetes, agentruntime, codeinterpreter, sandbox, api-reference]\n6: ---\n7: \n8: # CRD Reference\n9: \n10: AgentCube defines three Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) that serve as the declarative API for managing sandbox workloads.\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## AgentRuntime\n15: \n16: <K8sResource group=\"runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh\" version=\"v1alpha1\" kind=\"AgentRuntime\" scope=\"Namespaced\" yamlExample={`apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\n17: kind: AgentRuntime\n18: metadata:\n19:   name: my-agent\n20:   namespace: default\n21: spec:\n22:   targetPort:\n23:     - name: http\n24:       port: 8080\n25:       protocol: HTTP\n26:       pathPrefix: /api\n27:   podTemplate:\n28:     labels:\n29:       app: my-agent\n30:     annotations:\n31:       agentcube.volcano.sh/idle-timeout: \"30\"\n32:     spec:\n33:       containers:\n34:         - name: agent\n35:           image: my-registry/my-agent:latest\n36:           ports:\n37:             - containerPort: 8080\n38:           resources:\n39:             requests:\n40:               cpu: 100m\n41:               memory: 128Mi\n42:             limits:\n43:               cpu: 500m\n44:               memory: 512Mi\n45:   sessionTimeout: 30m\n46:   maxSessionDuration: 8h`} />\n47: \n48: `AgentRuntime` defines a long-running agent service template. When instantiated, it creates a sandbox pod running the specified container image.\n49: \n50: ### Spec Fields\n51: \n52: | Field | Type | Required | Default | Description |\n53: |-------|------|----------|---------|-------------|\n54: | `targetPort[]` | array | No | — | List of ports exposed by the sandbox |\n55: | `targetPort[].name` | string | No | — | Port name identifier |\n56: | `targetPort[].port` | uint32 | Yes | — | Port number |\n57: | `targetPort[].protocol` | string | Yes | — | Protocol: `\"HTTP\"` or `\"HTTPS\"` |\n58: | `targetPort[].pathPrefix` | string | No | — | URL path prefix for routing |\n59: | `podTemplate` | object | Yes | — | Pod template for sandbox creation |\n60: | `podTemplate.labels` | map[string]string | No | — | Labels applied to the sandbox pod |\n61: | `podTemplate.annotations` | map[string]string | No | — | Annotations applied to the sandbox pod |\n62: | `podTemplate.spec` | corev1.PodSpec | Yes | — | Standard Kubernetes Pod spec |\n63: | `sessionTimeout` | duration | No | — | Idle timeout duration before cleanup |\n64: | `maxSessionDuration` | duration | No | `8h` | Maximum total session lifetime |\n65: \n66: ### Status Fields\n67: \n68: | Field | Type | Description |\n69: |-------|------|-------------|\n70: | `conditions[]` | []metav1.Condition | Standard Kubernetes condition array |\n71: | `conditions[].type` | string | Condition type (e.g., `\"Ready\"`) |\n72: | `conditions[].status` | string | Condition status: `\"True\"`, `\"False\"`, `\"Unknown\"` |\n73: | `conditions[].reason` | string | Machine-readable reason for the condition |\n74: | `conditions[].message` | string | Human-readable message |\n75: | `conditions[].lastTransitionTime` | time | Time of last status transition |\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: ## CodeInterpreter\n80: \n81: <K8sResource group=\"runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh\" version=\"v1alpha1\" kind=\"CodeInterpreter\" scope=\"Namespaced\" yamlExample={`apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\n82: kind: CodeInterpreter\n83: metadata:\n84:   name: python-sandbox\n85:   namespace: default\n86: spec:\n87:   ports:\n88:     - name: picod\n89:       port: 8081\n90:       protocol: HTTP\n91:   template:\n92:     image: agentcube/picod:latest\n93:     imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent\n94:     resources:\n95:       requests:\n96:         cpu: 100m\n97:         memory: 128Mi\n98:       limits:\n99:         cpu: 1\n100:         memory: 512Mi\n101:   sessionTimeout: 30m\n102:   maxSessionDuration: 8h\n103:   warmPoolSize: 2\n104:   authMode: picod`} />\n105: \n106: `CodeInterpreter` defines a code execution sandbox template. It uses the PicoD engine for secure code execution and supports a warm pool for fast session startup.\n107: \n108: ### Spec Fields\n109: \n110: | Field | Type | Required | Default | Description |\n111: |-------|------|----------|---------|-------------|\n112: | `ports[]` | array | No | — | List of target ports exposed by the sandbox |\n113: | `ports[].name` | string | No | — | Port name identifier |\n114: | `ports[].port` | uint32 | Yes | — | Port number |\n115: | `ports[].protocol` | string | Yes | — | Protocol: `\"HTTP\"` or `\"HTTPS\"` |\n116: | `template` | object | Yes | — | Sandbox template specification |\n117: | `template.labels` | map[string]string | No | — | Labels applied to the sandbox pod |\n118: | `template.annotations` | map[string]string | No | — | Annotations applied to the sandbox pod |\n119: | `template.runtimeClassName` | string | No | — | Runtime class for the sandbox pod |\n120: | `template.image` | string | No | — | Container image for the sandbox |\n121: | `template.imagePullPolicy` | string | No | `IfNotPresent` | Image pull policy |\n122: | `template.imagePullSecrets` | array | No | — | Secrets for pulling private images |\n123: | `template.environment` | array | No | — | Environment variables (corev1.EnvVar) |\n124: | `template.command` | array | No | — | Container entrypoint command |\n125: | `template.args` | array | No | — | Container entrypoint arguments |\n126: | `template.resources` | object | No | — | Resource requests and limits |\n127: | `sessionTimeout` | duration | No | — | Idle timeout duration before cleanup |\n128: | `maxSessionDuration` | duration | No | `8h` | Maximum total session lifetime |\n129: | `warmPoolSize` | int32 | No | `0` | Number of pre-warmed sandbox instances |\n130: | `authMode` | string | No | `\"picod\"` | Authentication mode: `\"picod\"` or `\"none\"` |\n131: \n132: ### Status Fields\n133: \n134: | Field | Type | Description |\n135: |-------|------|-------------|\n136: | `conditions[]` | []metav1.Condition | Standard Kubernetes condition array |\n137: | `ready` | boolean | Whether the CodeInterpreter is ready to accept sessions |\n138: \n139: ### Warm Pool Mechanism\n140: \n141: The warm pool pre-provisions sandbox instances to reduce session startup latency:\n142: \n143: 1. **Configuration**: Set `warmPoolSize` to the desired number of pre-warmed instances\n144: 2. **Pre-provisioning**: WorkloadManager creates sandbox pods in advance, marked as available\n145: 3. **Session Claim**: When a new session is requested, an existing warm pod is claimed immediately\n146: 4. **Replenishment**: WorkloadManager creates a new warm pod to replace the claimed one\n147: 5. **Scaling**: If `warmPoolSize` is `0`, sandboxes are created on-demand (no warm pool)\n148: \n149: ```\n150: Warm Pool Workflow:\n151: \n152: ┌─────────────┐    Session     ┌─────────────┐\n153: │  Warm Pod 1 │────Request────▶│  Active      │\n154: │  (Ready)    │               │  Sandbox     │\n155: └─────────────┘               └─────────────┘\n156:                                       │\n157: ┌─────────────┐                       │\n158: │  Warm Pod 2 │                       │\n159: │  (Ready)    │◄────Replenish─────────┘\n160: └─────────────┘\n161: ```\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ## Sandbox\n166: \n167: <K8sResource group=\"agents.x-k8s.io\" version=\"v1alpha1\" kind=\"Sandbox\" scope=\"Namespaced\" yamlExample={`apiVersion: agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1\n168: kind: Sandbox\n169: metadata:\n170:   name: my-sandbox\n171:   namespace: default\n172: spec:\n173:   image: agentcube/sandbox:latest\n174:   command: \"python -m http.server 8080\"\n175: status:\n176:   phase: Running`} />\n177: \n178: `Sandbox` is a lower-level resource that represents an individual sandbox pod instance. It is typically managed by higher-level controllers (WorkloadManager) rather than created directly by users.\n179: \n180: ### Spec Fields\n181: \n182: | Field | Type | Required | Description |\n183: |-------|------|----------|-------------|\n184: | `image` | string | No | Container image for the sandbox |\n185: | `command` | string | No | Command to run in the sandbox container |\n186: \n187: ### Status Fields\n188: \n189: | Field | Type | Description |\n190: |-------|------|-------------|\n191: | `phase` | string | Current phase: `\"Pending\"`, `\"Running\"`, `\"Terminated\"` |\n192: \n193: ---\n194: \n195: ## SandboxClaim\n196: \n197: `SandboxClaim` is an extension resource used in conjunction with the warm pool mechanism.\n198: \n199: | Property | Value |\n200: |----------|-------|\n201: | API Group | `extensions.agents.x-k8s.io` |\n202: | Version | `v1alpha1` |\n203: | Kind | `SandboxClaim` |\n204: | Scope | Namespaced |\n205: \n206: ### Relationship with Warm Pool\n207: \n208: 1. When a session is requested, a `SandboxClaim` is created\n209: 2. The WorkloadManager matches the claim with an available warm sandbox\n210: 3. If no warm sandbox is available, a new sandbox is provisioned\n211: 4. Once matched, the claim is deleted and the session is established\n212: \n213: This decouples session request from sandbox provisioning, enabling faster session startup when warm pools are configured.\n214: \n215: ---\n216: \n217: ## API Group Summary\n218: \n219: | CRD | API Group | Version | Scope |\n220: |-----|-----------|---------|-------|\n221: | AgentRuntime | `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh` | v1alpha1 | Namespaced |\n222: | CodeInterpreter | `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh` | v1alpha1 | Namespaced |\n223: | Sandbox | `agents.x-k8s.io` | v1alpha1 | Namespaced |\n224: | SandboxClaim | `extensions.agents.x-k8s.io` | v1alpha1 | Namespaced |\n\n(End of file - total 224 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nsidebar_position: 3\ntitle: CRD Reference\ndescription: Kubernetes Custom Resource Definitions for AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter, and Sandbox\nkeywords: [crd, kubernetes, agentruntime, codeinterpreter, sandbox, api-reference]\n---\n\n# CRD Reference\n\nAgentCube defines three Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) that serve as the declarative API for managing sandbox workloads.\n\n---\n\n## AgentRuntime\n\n<K8sResource group=\"runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh\" version=\"v1alpha1\" kind=\"AgentRuntime\" scope=\"Namespaced\" yamlExample={`apiVersion: runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1\nkind: AgentRuntime\nmetadata:\n  name: my-agent\n  namespace: default","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/docs/docs/api-reference/crds.md","time":{"start":1775901604159,"end":1775901604165}}}}
